[6] Selected media reports and official press releases of interest
A. Cruise Ships - Australia
Date: Sat 21 Mar 2020 3:56PM AEDT
Source: News.com.au [edited]
https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/health-problems/coronavirus-australia-five-cruises-from-sydney-infected-with-covid19/news-story/5c0e5a4e6f68112f160f628ee5437768


NSW [New South Wales] Health has named 4 cruise ships as having confirmed cases of coronavirus with one of those ships having done 2 trips, bringing the total number of cruises identified to 5. More than 2600 passengers who were on the Ruby Princess cruise ship, operated by Princess Cruises, disembarked in Sydney on Thursday morning [19 Mar 2020]. At least 3 passengers and a crew member have since tested positive for coronavirus.

A couple who left the ship in Sydney and then flew to Darwin are among the positive results. In an update on Saturday afternoon [21 Mar 2020], the health department said, "NSW Health has identified 4 separate cruises affected by COVID-19, in addition to the Ruby Princess reported previously."

The additional cruises are as follows:
- Ovation of the Seas, leaving Sydney on [11 Mar 2020] and returning on [18 Mar 2020]
- Voyager of the Seas, leaving Sydney on [25 Feb 2020] and returning on [7 Mar 2020]
- Voyager of the Seas, leaving Sydney on [7 Mar 2020] and returning on [18 Mar 2020]
- Celebrity Solstice, confirmed case joined the ship in Auckland on [10 Mar 2020], docked in Sydney on [20 Mar 2020]

NSW Health said all passengers are being contacted to ensure self-quarantine although self isolation of "well passengers" on the trip arriving back on [7 Mar 2020] is no longer required as the 14-day advisory period has passed.

Ovation of the Seas
-------------------
NSW Health has identified a 67-year-old man who travelled from Canada before boarding a week-long cruise from Sydney on [11 Mar 2020] to [18 Mar 2020] as being diagnosed with coronavirus [COVID-19]. The Ovation of the Seas trip did not stop at any overseas locations.

"There are no known linked cases, no evidence of an outbreak of respiratory illness on the ship, or people who developed symptoms on the last day of the cruise," the health department said in a statement on Saturday [21 Mar 2020] . "The ship is now at sea with only crew on board." Passengers are advised to be alert for the development of any symptoms and should self-quarantine.

Voyager of the Seas
-------------------
Passengers on back-to-back Voyager of the Seas trips have tested positive for COVID-19. The 1st case was a young woman in her 20s travelling from [25 Feb 2020] to [7 Mar 2020]. The cruise ship visited the South Pacific and New Zealand. "There are no known linked cases, and no evidence of an outbreak of respiratory illness on board," NSW Health said. At 6.30am on Saturday [21 Mar 2020] it had been 14 days since the ship arrived back in Sydney. "Although self-isolation of well passengers is no longer required, all passengers are being contacted with advice to seek COVID-19 testing if unwell," the state's health department said.

Earlier on Saturday [21 Mar 2020], health authorities sent an email advising Voyager of the Seas passengers that a passenger was "infectious while on the ship" for the [7 Mar 2020] to [18 Mar 2020] cruise. A 66-year-old man from South Australia was confirmed as having the coronavirus on Friday [20 Mar 2020]. He is in a Sydney hospital. "There are no known linked cases and no evidence of an outbreak of respiratory illness on board," NSW Health repeated.

The department urged those who travelled on the Royal Caribbean-operated cruise ship, that arrived in Sydney on Wednesday [18 Mar 2020], to self-isolate for 14 days at home following the revelation. The Voyager of the Seas had taken passengers on an 11-night South Pacific cruise. Royal Caribbean sent a statement to guests "in conjunction with NSW Public Health and in an abundance of caution" in the early hours of Saturday [21 Mar 2020] morning. "This person was diagnosed after disembarking and was infectious while on the ship," the health department said in the email," seen by http://news.com.au. All passengers have been advised they are "considered a close contact" and needed to remain in home isolation for a fortnight after they disembarked, up to the morning of [1 Apr 2020].

"We are working with public health authorities in Australia and New Zealand. We appreciate their efforts and are co-operating with their requests," a Royal Caribbean International spokesperson told news.com.au on Saturday [21 Mar 2020]. The ship was called into Sydney early on Tuesday [17 Mar 2020] for a medical evacuation after a guest suffered a stroke. It resumed sailing before returning to Circular Quay on Wednesday [18 Mar 2020].

Celebrity Solstice
------------------
Celebrity Solstice, which docked in Sydney on Friday [20 Mar 2020], is the 4th of the vessels to have a passenger diagnosed with the coronavirus. "New Zealand has advised that a male passenger on the Celebrity Solstice, which docked in Sydney on [20 Mar 2020], was reported today to have COVID-19," NSW Health said on Saturday [21 Mar 2020]. "The case had joined the ship at the beginning of the cruise in Auckland on [10 Mar 2020] and left it in Dunedin on [15 Mar 2020]. "There are no known linked cases and no evidence of an outbreak of respiratory illness on board, all passengers are being contacted to ensure self-quarantine and to provide advice to monitor for symptoms."

[Byline: Sarah McPhee]

--
Communicate by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[The cruise ship sagas continue... One can't help but wonder how compliant people are with voluntary self-quarantine as a recommendation. It awaits to be seen if there are chains of transmission that lead back to passengers on one of these cruise ships. As I said in yesterday's post, given the nature of this pandemic organism (SARS-CoV-2) that seems to transmit rapidly and somewhat silently before the storm, one has to seriously consider if there should be a moratorium on cruise ship sailings. - Mod.MPP]

