[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 outside China continues to grow and now totals 174. This includes 15 countries (including 3 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 58 countries (including 6 territories) from the European region, 8 from the Southeast Asia region, 19 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 42 countries (including 10 territories) from the Americas region, and 32 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

Looking at the European region, transmission was at a very low level until 22 Feb 2020, when Italy reported an increase from 9 cases to 76 cases overnight (https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/situation-reports/20200223-sitrep-34-covid-19.pdf?sfvrsn=44ff8fd3_2, now in less than 1 month, the total number of cases in Europe has surpassed 100 000 cases (compare with it taking almost 3 months for the global case count to reach 100 000). Italy accounts for 39.2% of the total confirmed cases in the region and 30.4% of the newly confirmed case in the 24 hours covered by this report. Spain, Germany, and France account for 37.3% of the total reported cases and 31.3% of the newly confirmed cases.

Sobering information is the time it took to reach the 1st 100 000 cases (almost 3 months) and the time it took to reach the 2nd 100 000 cases -- 12 days and at the rate we are progressing, arrival at 300 000 cases will be in the next 24 hours (see the Worldometer data in section [1] above).

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases reported outside of China, by date of report and WHO region through [19 Mar 2020], at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic in China, juxtaposed with the increasing epidemics outside of China. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and now the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA but other countries are following suit. It would be very nice to see an epidemic curve based on date of onset of illness.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: it is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have at times significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and, depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the Hopkins table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
